French Tragedies Dataset¶

Data Source: https://www.kaggle.com/sharkcpn/french-tragedies The dataset contains 59 text documents in French Language.

Objective:¶

estimate the sentiment in these documents
i.e calculate if individual documents are of positive or negative sentiment
additionaly classify them into further categories of sentiments

FEEL Lexicon¶

French Expanded Emotion Lexicon (FEEL)

FEEL is a French lexicon containing more than 14 000 distinct words expressing emotions and sentiments. It follows the Ekman basic two polarities and six emotions (Ekman, 1992). It has been created by automatically translating and expanding the English Emotional Lexicon NRC-Canada (Mohammad & Turney, 2013). The process has been supervised and validated manually by a human professional translator.

Link: http://advanse.lirmm.fr/feel.php

# Save all the text to sqlite database of easy access later

files = os.listdir('dataset/')

with sqlite3.connect('french_tragedies.db') as conn:
    curr = conn.cursor()
    curr.execute('DROP TABLE IF EXISTS French_tragedies;')
    curr.execute('CREATE TABLE French_tragedies(Filename text NOT NULL, Text text);')
    for filename in tqdm(files):
        with open('dataset/'+ filename, encoding='utf-8') as file:
            text = file.read().replace('\n', '')
            curr.execute('insert into French_tragedies(Filename, Text) values (?, ?);', (filename, text))

Approach 1¶

For a given text document count the find the words that are in our lexicon and count their polarity and emotions.

Since our lexicon dictionary has words of length 1 to 6. We will try to look for all of them

In [26]:
# https://stackoverflow.com/a/6822773
def window(seq, n=2):
    '''
    Returns a sliding window (of width n) over data from the iterable
       s -> (s0,s1,...s[n-1]), (s1,s2,...,sn), ...
    '''
    it = iter(seq)
    result = tuple(islice(it, n))
    if len(result) == n:
        yield result
    for elem in it:
        result = result[1:] + (elem,)
        yield result


def get_sentiment(sent):
    '''
    yields the sentiments of words found in lexicon
    for each window of length 1 to 6 in sent
    '''
    for window_size in range(6, 0, -1):
        for each in window(sent.split(), window_size):
            sub_str = ' '.join(each)
            try:
                sentiment = lexicon.loc[sub_str]
                
                # remove that phrase so that we don't see it for smaller window
                sent.replace(sub_str, '')
                
                yield sentiment
            except KeyError:
                # if phrase not in lexicon ignore and continue
                pass

def gen_sentiments(text):
    '''
    Returns a pandas series containing sentiment count of the text
    '''
    # remove redundant white spaces
    text = ' '.join(text.split())
    
    # Split the text on punctuations to get sentences
    sents = re.split(r'[,?!\.;:]', text)
    
    # Sentiment features to count
    features = {
        'polarity_diff': 0, # diff. of positive and negative polarity
        'joy':0,
        'fear': 0,
        'sadness': 0,
        'anger': 0,
        'surprise': 0,
        'disgust': 0
    }
    for sent in sents:
        for sentiment in get_sentiment(sent):
            if sentiment['polarity'] == 'positive':
                features['polarity_diff'] += 1
            else:
                # if the word is negative reduce the overall polarity
                features['polarity_diff'] -= 1
            features['joy'] += sentiment['joy']
            features['fear'] += sentiment['fear']
            features['sadness'] += sentiment['sadness']
            features['anger'] += sentiment['anger']
            features['surprise'] += sentiment['surprise']
            features['disgust'] += sentiment['disgust']
    
    return pd.Series(features)

Approach 2 (cleaned text)¶

Instead of raw text now lets try counting the sentiment and emotion properties on cleaned text data.

We will be using spacy for tokenizaion, lemmatization, and pos tagging as it has support for french lannguage for npl tasks

In [34]:
def cleaned_sentiment(text):
    
    doc = nlp(text)
    features = {
        'polarity_diff': 0, # diff. of positive and negative polarity
        'joy':0,
        'fear': 0,
        'sadness': 0,
        'anger': 0,
        'surprise': 0,
        'disgust': 0
    }
    for token in doc:
        # Lemmatize the word
        cleaned_token = token.lemma_
        try:
            sentiment = lexicon.loc[cleaned_token]
            if sentiment['polarity'] == 'positive':
                features['polarity_diff'] += 1
            else:
                # if the word is negative reduce the overall polarity
                features['polarity_diff'] -= 1
            features['joy'] += sentiment['joy']
            features['fear'] += sentiment['fear']
            features['sadness'] += sentiment['sadness']
            features['anger'] += sentiment['anger']
            features['surprise'] += sentiment['surprise']
            features['disgust'] += sentiment['disgust']
        except KeyError:
            pass
    return pd.Series(features)

Approach 3 (Use only adjectives and adverbs)¶

Now lets try only considering adjectives and adverbs as these types of words are the most important in classification of sentiment

In [40]:
def cleaned_sentiment(text):
    doc = nlp(text)
    features = {
        'polarity_diff': 0, # diff. of positive and negative polarity
        'joy':0,
        'fear': 0,
        'sadness': 0,
        'anger': 0,
        'surprise': 0,
        'disgust': 0
    }
    for token in doc:
        # consider only those words which are detected
        # as adjective or adverb
        if token.pos_ == 'ADV' or token.pos_ == 'ADJ':
            # taking the lemmatize form
            cleaned_token = token.lemma_
            try:
                sentiment = lexicon.loc[cleaned_token]
                if sentiment['polarity'] == 'positive':
                    features['polarity_diff'] += 1
                else:
                    # if the word is negative reduce the overall polarity
                    features['polarity_diff'] -= 1
                features['joy'] += sentiment['joy']
                features['fear'] += sentiment['fear']
                features['sadness'] += sentiment['sadness']
                features['anger'] += sentiment['anger']
                features['surprise'] += sentiment['surprise']
                features['disgust'] += sentiment['disgust']
            except KeyError:
                pass
    return pd.Series(features)

Document Classification¶

Since our approach 3 which only uses adjectives and adverbs for counting features looks somewhat promising.

Lets try to classify based on the polarity score stat we obtained.

i.e if polarity_diff is positive then the document has positive sentiment else the document has negative sentiment

We can use the emotions to compare it it with other documents as how good it if compared to other documents.
Example: if the percentile score of joy emotion is 90% then it has more text that represents joy that 90% of the document

In [47]:
# to get the percentile score
from scipy.stats import percentileofscore
In [60]:
emotion_labels = ['joy', 'fear', 'sadness', 'anger', 'surprise', 'disgust']

def print_report(index):
    '''
    Prints the polarity and emotion percentile bar graph
    compared to other document
    '''
    print('Document:', row['Filename'])
    polarity = 'positive' if sentiment_features.loc[index]['polarity_diff'] > 0 else 'negative'
    print('Polarity:', polarity)
    emotions = {}
    for label in emotion_labels:
        emotions[label] = percentileofscore(sentiment_features[label], sentiment_features.loc[index][label])
    
    # Sort by values (highest value first)
    emotions = pd.Series(emotions)#.sort_values()
    emotions.plot(kind='barh', xlim=(0, 100));
    plt.show();
